The paper deals with combinatorial designs and cryptography, which are topics typically found in the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) and Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-categories. The use of Latin squares and orthogonal arrays suggests a connection to Information Theory (cs.IT) and Error-Correcting Codes (cs.CC). Finally, the use of matrices in the characterization of orthogonal Latin squares suggests a connection to Systems and Control (cs.SY).
